The first virtual operator will be arriving this year in the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It probably won't be long before we get there.
That the Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed this by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU) who warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive in the Union.
Following the recent steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming fee regulation, it is likely to reach a paradoxical situation - for some clients of Czech mobile operators, SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This is probably paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition on the Czech market.
As a result, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), Pavel Dvořák, has already stated that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant price drop to which classic operators should also react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can be successful.
On the other hand, there is no need to look too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to get over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, it is enough for many fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in building, operating and maintaining the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled at low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, it often contrasts with the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers at least half of the cheap SMS with respect to competition.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland, it can also be a good blow for a trivial goal group.
This operator is specifically addressed to man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - is the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is hard to say whether it seems like a Polish concept could get stuck in our country.
This is why Vodafone's spokesman, Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of the supply of services is relatively saturated"
There are no possibilities in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there are any virtual operators in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in Czech R. doesn't seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," he said in telephone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly it ensured that current mobile telephony operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Instead, they try to do everything possible to prevent any potential competition from occurring.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows it by the GTS Novera group that I would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile telephony operators.
With some of them we have been able to make progress at the meetings," said the group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe they're flashing better times.
It seems that, for informal information, the first official operator would have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this point we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
To date no one has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this field," he said for mobile.cz, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesperson for Telefónica O2.
Other operators are concerned with the specificity of the Czech market.
The spokesperson for T-mobile, Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And add: "On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short horizon"
Vodafone directs its attention rather to meeting the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this with regard to the distribution of expenditure and infrastructure.
We precisely regard it as the biggest contribution from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is found in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with operators and meat
The progress of mobile operators can easily be understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a price drop and thus a decrease in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of that is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure to the ČTU was at the time of the entry of U:phone by T-Mobile society.
It is attested to by accessible public information on the ČTU websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrova adds this: "Also, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the market for mobile telephony in the Czech Republic, it is natural that another player's entry into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services large requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Bids (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
To date, no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for classic operators," Kristian Chalupa, from the UOHS Department of Foreign Relations, added to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers, it is something more than a consideration, apart from that, they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In abroad where virtual operators operate normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop of mobile telephony services"
Obviously, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market media and the price drop does not fall within the interest of the UOHS.
It's really dramatic in this whole case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no sign of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore, they do not have a corresponding rise in liability in their market actions.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunication regulators," added Chalupa's response.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets developed by ČTU that telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial bidding a single market.
On this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile telephony operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for UOHS should represent a warning that three mobile operators are strikingly lit in a similar way.
Current complaints from stakeholders (inflationed by GTS Novera society) show that in all negotiations with operators there are many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in the ČTU is a quite common trick in the field of telecommunications from which UOHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately a new amendment was introduced recently to the Telecommunications Act for the expansion of the competition of ČTU in the field of commercial tenders that did not take effect, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be well known by the representatives of UOHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks
At the same time, unawarely, something still works as well as a pseudo-virtual operator that in the Czech mobile telephone networks there are a few already.
They are companies that place their own prices on mobile telephony services which, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are dedicated to multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only some chosen ones get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the company by commissioning a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will receive after special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be discovered, you could talk about infringements in terms of contract conditions that could be translated into the end of collaboration with the given society," replied the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that a kind of activity carried out by mobile telephony operators would not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, they may become thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get no negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a despicable as many percent of customers.
These must also accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so you cannot have it absolutely as a normal customer of operators."
Precisely this is what should seem to the ČTU at least strange.
There is also a new question for UOHS.
If mobile telephony operators are around their eyes in this type of procedure, why are they blocking the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it it should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their trading conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market resulted in a significant decrease in service prices.
At the same time, almost all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classic operators tried to protect themselves from this breach.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, eventually too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases have defended operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they made the first virtual operator emerge and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body goes through this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
Through our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of the powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this information between backstages is correct and the virtual operator actually arrives at these lands, then the Czech market of mobile telephony is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators allows any virtual mobile telephony operator to enter, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the hymn Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one male voice and one female voice, one with Coro and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are responsible for this.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said before it intentionally chose for the solo singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with the two and then, also, with the Choir that were fixed in the dictionary so that the text would be well understood, so that it would have consonance," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates next year's 175th anniversary.
The song Where, my Home played for the first time in 1834 in the tables of the Theatre of States in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It won popularity and people made it their own.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
