The MHD in Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, is written in the history of the Prague Transportation Company the date on which the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic bonus in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be acquired right now by nearly 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day bonus and the annual bonus (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card in the infocentres and posts of the transport company at Metro stations, Museum, Mŏstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Bonuses can be purchased from yesterday online on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, up to the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start forgetting the ticket sales posts at the metro stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get out a regular ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged to you in one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there are passengers at their disposal a window with prepared staff that helps stakeholders with the purchase on the Internet and also with the reloading of the bonus purchased on their card," said the project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic bonus on the Opencard on the vending machines that are found in some subway halls.
How are these exduding machines?
They are red, they remind us of a billing machine and travelers will probably have already set themselves in them at the stations of the Roztyly Metro, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný completed.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be loaded only on it.
E-bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, in the roundabout trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of the localities of Central Bohemia.
"In the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reader card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the bonus area," explained the ticket control, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that sets the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
The roundabout buses have their reading cards mounted on the driver's locker.
When entering it it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany it with the Opencard at the location intended for it on the side of the box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonds there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not travel on the roundabout buses and do not remember when they are finished the validity of the bonus can be addressed to the expent machines where the cards are reloaded.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information on the validity of your document.
