The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday his 10th anniversary of his foundation, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec has returned to be one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public that he had seriously been hesitant about the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster could no longer be reproduced.
While Judge Krever was late in presenting his relationship, certain provinces then established a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work during the years that followed, we have regained the confidence of the public ", says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary nevertheless recalls that " confidence is extremely fragile " .
Since its inception, on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended the birth in Europe of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emerge from it, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been shown out of all doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive technique of HIV detection appeared on the market: the nucleid acid tests that allow the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors, which have been based on the tests used so far.
Tests of nucleid acid allowed the period between the moment the person has been infected and the moment the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We could reduce this period in less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements allowed the risk of contracting AIDS significantly for blood transfusions.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products every year, more than 24 years will pass before a case of transmission of HIV to a blood product occurs.
I believe that one can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without concern," says the head of Héma-Québec's management.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Meeting, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You must be constantly vigilant ", pursue Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide for sufficient supplies.
" Needs increase because the population ages.
Since the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need red blood cells or platelet injection.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the network of blood donors that regroups on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All people with good health, aged 18, who meet the eligibility criteria, however, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory covering the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and urge them to be regular donors.
Since today's life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood," says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered as biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of severe diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, placing in the bank of our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord and it is expected to take more than a thousand of these a year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year," said Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this " , since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
