Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
On September 17, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J . Garver, Vice-President and Director of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold states that the largest gold company in the world attempted a process of defamation of six million euros against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a " transparent public debate " .
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of persecution by defamation, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to have a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his own?
The outcome of the complaint is of little importance, the authors and the editor of the book Noir Canada must spend considerable amounts in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the miner.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will dampen the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to consider the matter again.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that he would have had to present his vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are usually made by changing ideas rather than by punching.
It was therefore enough for the miner to open her books, her files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and reject requests and supporting letters for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he could request a "public" debate by disregarding his views?
According to the vice-president, this word seems to designate only paid lawyers and not all Canadians; it represents a very limited view of the concept.
