Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan that aims to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
It particularly foresees: better control by the elected parties of their implementation, of new mechanisms aimed at ensuring the reimbursement of the invested public money, of new provisions to contain the number of excluded houses the lack of payment, as well as a right of control over wages paid to the leaders of the relief companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We are making great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on the American daily life will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect that would cause a new failure in the mood of investors.
The last hour they had set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, which have acceded late to the negotiations, were more favourable to the agreement, but not forgetting to express their satisfaction at being forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly that would enable the owners to keep their home and the salary of the leaders of the State-surviving companies.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, no one should be congratulated.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, interrogated in another chain to know if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied that: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it."
"The important points I read [show] that is something we will have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
He said that the option of not doing anything is not acceptable ".
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money dubious debts, risky and unspoiled assets from the American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the outbreak of a real estate bubble which first led to the sinking of mortgage risk credits before extending to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and causing a freezing of liquidity and abandonment of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe that we have been out of stagnation since Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only secured by the government rather than purchased.
In order to clean up everyone's asperities in Congress, we also added a provision that stipulated that if the government had to bear losses for five years with this program, it could impose new rates that would attempt to help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to which another 100 billion may be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote from Congress.
In exchange for your help, Washington will get shares in the relief companies that will benefit it dividends in case of profits and that it will be able to sell again when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying embargo procedures for housing obtained from real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on remuneration and on metal compensation paid to the leaders of companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote by the House of Representatives today and the Senate next Wednesday.
Despite all its efforts, it is not yet certain that its plan will be adopted.
Some people continued to protest yesterday against this project, both by Republicans and Democrats.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the chamber finance commission, told his voters that "with all evidence, Washington does not want to understand."
" We have a very serious financial problem.
There are solutions.
But not that of taking advantage of the taxpayers. "
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, who is encouraging a small group in Congress, presented the problems differently, but came to the same conclusion.
" Four hundred professors of economics, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to tell us: we ask Congress not to rush and carefully examine the way to be taken," he said yesterday.
At this very moment, in Europe, we again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an urgent meeting, the three Benelux countries announced partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion dollars).
The intervention by the Governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had refused to purchase its competitor in bankruptcy since it lost 2 billion euros (US$ 2.9 billion) during the crisis of venture real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is part of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said the Dutch Minister of Finance yesterday, Wouter Bos.
On the other hand, we have recovered a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It is just something that the savers and families will now appreciate that the times are uncertain."
During this time, across the Channel, the British government seemed to want to nationalize another bank in the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans at the Bradford and Bringley bank and more than EUR 41 billion ($75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would be the one to buy the British bank’s branches and bank accounts.
The Bradford and Bringley Bank would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government would have to nationalize from the beginning of this financial crisis.
