Psychology of Overlays: Why Do We Spend More Money?
The auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
The neurologists and economists of the University of New York discovered the neurological bases - economics of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in a auction and while being examined through the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (MRI) the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could earn money , but during auctions, where it is fundamental element to bet more than the other, by losing the game increased the operation of the complex called stratum located below the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "auto-prime" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, increased betting is explained as a prevention not to cause an intense reaction to the stratum.
To substantiate its theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups wagered against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members betted.
The other group was promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, even those members of the group lost that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that one highlighted the triumph and the other the failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to wager even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
Those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and preventing risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation" - established Andrew Schotter, professor of the University of New York University's economic faculty.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
Around the world some five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
It is estimated at 100,000 in this country, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread in two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with contaminated water or food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vagina humor, saliva).
It is recommended that travellers be protected by vaccine against virus A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after eating the infected food, manifested by a general poor condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear in the skin and white of the eyes jaundice, excrement becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected is treated pharmacologically.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of the infected do not know you are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are now about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to eliminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
On 30 September it was World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and to the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less who they believe in God?
According to a recent study, religious faith has a soothing effect that also alleviated the death of martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
Within the framework of this singular experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists applied electric shock while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was found that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of the research series in which academics also participate in scientists, philosophers and theologians from different departments of the University.
The analysis was carried out as follows: a sharp instrument was attached to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to set their eyes on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, work of 17th century Sassoferrato and the Lady of the Armain of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary's spectacle would cause a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour in an MRI scan, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during this period while observing the painting of religious theme or the other.
Catholics stated that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and in their hearts peace reigned."
By observing the religious theme picture, they felt about 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so striking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person who feels very positively, as if by a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases truly change our personality" - Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of her size were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary bring even better results?
