The intelligent car imitates the flight of the baby
What would be the best method of developing technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, that of beekeepers.
In an amazing project presented at the Japan CEATEC, the beekeepers provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic management system of cars type BR23C imitating nature, to which the characteristics of the beeches were given, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each baby creates its own private ovalated space that actually looks a lot like our safe capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the compound eyes of beeches that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid the collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the beeches, modifying the direction by turning to the necessary extent the wheels.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is completely instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and of the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable interior layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bee.
This process must be carried out in an open and close the eyes.
However, unlike beeches, the movement cannot go up, down or diagonal, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the turn direction of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for beekeepers to dodge other beeches, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotating movement and the acceleration further the braking.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is greater, which means that they have a longer life span than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is instinctive and intelligent reaction, not data processing capacity, nor much less storage capacity.
This device in every second should only process some input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
You don't need gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into the models manufactured in series within ten years.
Another possibility for your application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding any obstacles in his path.
