On the bill called the Emergency Law for Economic Stabilization of 2008, the first Monday will vote for the U.S. Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also held news about the agreement.
We are pleased with the progress made during the night and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy - said Tony Fratto, the spokesperson for the White House.
The programme differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration to spend all 700 billion dollars on buying low-quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using 250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this amount, the Ministry of Finance will buy credit fund securities, poor rating and the other $100 billion target depends on the President's decision.
This programme will be controlled by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion may be spent after a new Congress decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: you can simultaneously buy bad credits, mortgages and credit fund securities, as well as other "veneous"-type credits as well.
