Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month’s prices and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 percent.
Internal sales prices in the processing industry increased at least by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8%), due firstly to the increase of 4.6 per cent per month of bags and belts and the increase of 2.5 per cent of footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the chemical production branch prices (1.6 per cent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the processing sectors of wood (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of paper manufacturing, publishing and printing.
In the rest of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4%).
There was an increase of 13.2 per cent in the metal processing sector, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
The prices of electricity, the supply of gas, heat and water exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly increase in prices (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in energy and intermediate sectors prices there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8%).
In the consumer goods producing branches there was a decrease of 6.8 per cent and in investment goods 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 percent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 percent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent with respect to the euro and 15.9 percent with respect to the dollar.
