Jároka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has been launched in Paris, and its host is France, who is also President-in-Office of the European Union this year.
Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message addressed to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, called attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that hit Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister of Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for jobs, social affairs and equal opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European social rights protection organisations attended the meeting.
Jároka - according to the press bureau of the Fidesz group of Members in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Roma are left out of the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"Most Roma young people have not finished middle school and because of the poor quality of basic education, only a small part can obtain university degrees."
Jároka further stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role to play in the prevalence of other human rights.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the Euro MP, these issues need to be widely conscious of both Roma and non-Gypsies.
As soon as the school starts, a Gypsy student will have more opportunities to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the European Parliament, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to speed up the process of school segregation immediately, so it is of fundamental importance that the proper implementation of existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is properly complied with.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and Roma children should be given the opportunity to guarantee democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights," Jároka demanded.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, organised annually since last year's Berlin meeting in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
